SignalDetectionTool: R Package for signal detection for surveillance data

SignalDetectionTool.Rmd

Running the App

Source the package

library(SignalDetectionTool)

and run the app

run_app()

Upload Data

The surveillance data to analyze must have the following format.

Variable Mandatory Type Description
case_id YES character or numeric Unique identifier for a specific case, but nothing that can be used to identify the case or patient within the national surveillance system
date_report YES character or date Date when the case was reported in ISO 8601 format YYYY-MM-DD
date_onset NO character or date Date when symptoms started in ISO 8601 format YYYY-MM-DD
date_hospitalization NO character or date Date when the case was admitted to the hospital in ISO 8601 format YYYY-MM-DD
date_death NO character or date Date when the case died in ISO 8601 format YYYY-MM-DD
date_vaccination NO character or date Date when the case was vaccinated in ISO 8601 format YYYY-MM-DD
country YES character Name of the country in which the case was reported
country_id YES character or numeric Id of the country in which the case was reported, Id should be NUTS-0 or ISO-alpha3 code
state NO character Name of the state/major region in which the case was reported
state_id NO character or numeric Id of the state as NUTS-1 code
county NO character Name of the county/basic region in which the case was reported
county_id NO character or numeric Id of the county as NUTS-2 code
community NO character Name of the community/small region in which the case was reported
community_id NO character or numeric Id of the community as NUTS-3 code
region_level1 NO character Name of the major region in which the case was reported, alternative to the state column
region_level1_id NO character or numeric Id of the region as specified in the shapefile
region_level2 NO character Name of the basic region in which the case was reported, alternative to the county column
region_level2_id NO character or numeric Id of the region as specified in the shapefile
region_level3 NO character Name of the small region in which the case was reported, alternative to the community column
region_level3_id NO character or numeric Id of the region as specified in the shapefile
age NO integer Age (in years) of the reported case at the time of reporting as integer between 0-125. Either age or age_group should be provided
age_group NO character Age group (in years) of the reported case at the time of reporting as interval. Either age or age_group should be provided. Allowed separators are -, —, _. For the first age group, it is allowed to use &lt; (e.g. &lt;10) but also use the separators (e.g. 00-10). For the last age group digit separator digit (i.e. 90-100 or 90_100 depending on your separator), digit+ (e.g. 100+) or &gt;digit (e.g. &gt;100) is allowed. For all age groups between the first and the last only one separator should be used.
sex NO character Sex of the reported case, one of male, female, diverse, unknown
occupation NO character Occupation of the reported case, possible options (not limited to): care, kindergarten, food production
place_of_infection NO character Name of the region in which the case was likely infected if that place is different from the reporting region
place_of_infection_id NO character or numeric Id of the region in which the case was likely infected as NUTS-code
pathogen YES character Name of the pathogen/diagnosis that was identified
pathogen_id NO character or numeric Id of the pathogen/diagnosis
subtype NO character Name of the subtype/serovar/variant that was identified
subtype_id NO character or numeric Id of the subtype/serovar/variant
hospitalization NO character Indication whether the case was hospitalized, yes, no or unknown
death NO character Indication whether the case has died, yes, no or unknown
vaccination NO character Indication whether the case was vaccinated before infection, yes, no or unknown
outbreak_status NO character Indication whether the case is known to be part of an outbreak, yes, no, unknown

Advanced Use

Preprocessing the data 

data <- preprocess_data(input_example)

Creating tables 

results <- get_signals(data, stratification = c("county", "sex", "age_group"))
build_signals_table(results)
